<?php include "../header/header.php"; ?><html><body><div class="container"><br><h1>Vectors and Normalizing</h1><br><br><b>Normalizing a Vector in Unity :</b><br><br><b>Vector :</b><br>a quantity possessing both magnitude and direction.<br><br><img src="../content/images/2020-12-13Untitled.png" width="600" height="600"><br><br><br><b>Example :</b> We can use a vector to represent the distance and the direction a ball moves when it is thrown with a some velocity (ignore concepts like acceleration or friction for simplicity).<br>A Vector holds 2 pieces of information - a point in space and a magnitude (vector length).<br><br><img src="../content/images/2020-12-132Untitled.png" width="700" height="600"><br><br><br>The direction would be the angle/path from the origin (0,0,0) point to the vector point in space.<br>So, the magnitude of the vector would be the distance traveled by the ball before stopping and the direction is also included.<br><br><b>Normalizing a Vector :</b><br>If a vector becomes normalized it keeps its direction but its length is set to one unit - So we only have a direction value.<br> <br>In practical usage, we can use vector normalization while implementing shooting system in a game. We need the direction of the bullet, we do not need the length - Ideally it must travel until it hits something / dies after a fixed distance(range).</div></body></html><br><br><?php include "../footer/footer.php"; ?>